I enjoyed working on this project! There were several challenges in terms of non-customary spelling and grammar in the survey participants' responses, and I encountered occasional difficulties in reading participants' handwriting. I tried to remain faithful to the nuances of each response,

including unusual word usage, in my translation. The file was clear and easy to read outside of handwriting issues.

Please note that the French work "plaidoyer" was used in three of the responses (pages 6, 29 and 33). I translated this as "advocacy" but there is an alternate translation which would be "plea" or "appeal" in the legal sense. The context suggests that the first translation of the word is correct, however, if the workshop in question did discuss specifics about how to make a legal appeal or plea, that word choice might need to be reconsidered. Please feel free to contact me with any questions on this.

I welcome your feedback, and thank you for entrusting me with this important translation project!

Best,

Arwen

Dear Sir/Madam\r\nThe reason this Polish translation of the Darwin storybook is being presented in this layout and format is due to the deficiencies of the original document provided for translation. Not only is the said [original] Word document poorly formatted which results in segments of text carrying over to next pages, but also whole section of the story and locked for editing i.e. not Word-translateable. It has been suggested that I should translate the editable sections and provide the rest of the translation in the form of captions â€“ however, this solution did not work out either. Word simply cannot handle the inclusion of so many long captions and as a result the entire document was freezing and/or going hayware. Therefore, after careful consideration, I have

decided to replicate the layout of the original document in a brand-new file, with clear indications for the DTP person as to which paragraph and sentence goes where.
Any questions with regard to translation can be directed to me at fuine2@gmail.com. Better yet, I would be very happy to have a look at the formatted/DTP-ed Polish version of the storybook when it is finished, so that any remaining glitches and mistakes can be remedied. For my part, I have translated Darwinâ€™s story with linguistic care, spell-checked it and reviewed it in terms of both contents and consistency of formatting etc. Hope you will find it acceptable. I certainly found it very interesting and educational for both kids and adults alike! :-)
Kind regards,
Barbara (Basia) Rompalska

There were many uneditable images for which the words had to be extracted for translation, resulting in the total word count being of 10,700 words instead of the announced 7,200. Because of the vast amount of uneditable text, I extracted all text and translated in

column form in a Word document which will need some DTP work as a result. Please note that I translated most quotes freely as I did not find any German versions of the books quoted, so in the reference section I translated "from" as "freely translated from". I did, however, find the original German quote from Ernst von Hesse-Wartegg in the "Frankfurter Zeitung und Handelsblatt" and updated the reference for the German version accordingly. Please note that the real nationality of Hesse-Wartegg is not known, but as he is believed to be Austrian, I translated "A writer visiting from Germany" literally, thereby avoiding mentioning a nationality or claiming him to be German when it is not sure whether he actually was. Please have the terms used in this translation cross-checked with other publications for the same organization, especially the terms "Lookout", "Thinker", "Investigator", "Plant Detective", "Discoverer", "Collector" and "thinking walk" that appear across different publications of the same organization.

'Il cieco' in English should be 'the blind person' or similar, not 'the blind'.
I would suggest the use of 'his' in non-gender-specific contexts is now unacceptable in most contexts. Use 'their' or 'his or her' to be sure.
UK English was specified, so 'theatre' not 'theater'.
'The series of blind' does not make sense. Indeed, Boal's exercises were published in English, and usually known as the 'blind series'.

Dear Sirs,

When using in your texts contextual contractions and/or abbreviations, ensure that somewhere in the text person can find a full name or notion. If such abbreviations are well-known and widely used within your organizations and documents, it can be totally unknown to people not dealing with them. And this can lead to misunderstanding first by translators, and second, by target audience.
So, please, be sure to give full names within a context at least once or make a general abbreviation glossary.

This leaflet was translated so poorly as to be unintelligible at times and needed more than proofreading to retain its informative function. For the most part, I re-translated it.\r\n\r\nThe file seemed to be machine translated at least in part, with no regard for grammar or accessibility to the target reader. The main problem was that names of many organizations and services (e.g. Community Welfare Service) were translated without leaving the original in place or even checking the customary

translations of these names in similar texts, which made the leaflet unusable for an actual person in need. Moreover, translation if the names was inconsistent.

I corrected quotation marks (changing â€œâ€ to â€žâ€), other punctuation errors, lack of Polish diacritic characters, double spaces and some formatting loss. I changed phrasing to be more accessible and eliminated calques. In one instance, the opening hours of an organization had been changed; I corrected that.

On page 2 and several times throughout the document, the translator rendered "homelessness" as "bezrobocie" - "unemployment", completely changing the meaning of that part of the text.
